<font color="#FF0000">A GOOK IS A GOOK</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul  6 10:50:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dear Doc, <br><br>
There is no comparison between our Civil War and the war in Vietnam. The South was invaded by communist soldiers from the North. They were armed, trainned and equipted by Communist block countries. We knew it and they knew its esclation into a WWIII confrontation with Russian and China Johnson played games with the lives of American soldiers and with the lives of the South Vietnamese citizen. The South Vietnames wanted to be left alone by both the North and could not stand corrupt officials in their government. That is why when they were given the opportunity in September of 1967 to vote over 80% did so. <br><br>
Gooks were gooks; it is a term we used in Nam to reflect the enemy and even ourselves. The language of the Vietnamese people was used in a very similar way it all depended upon who was hearing what you were saying and how you said it. The same word spoken to kinfolk's with a raise in the tone could mean an endearing note and if they spoke the same word to a stranger with a drop in the tone it may mean something totally different. To a Marine when the word gook is used in a combat situation, it means the enemy. In a story regarding villagers, it meant the civilian population without a negative or positive association. In a situation where your addressing or kidding around with a Marine of oriental features it was an endearing word much like the nicknames we picked up. &quot;Lucky&quot; was not lucky, or perhaps he was. Others had other nicknames. While everyone may have called each other, Bro (brother) in Nam during my time we did not experience the racial conflicts that developed afterwards. Blacks, Hispanics, we all shared the same hooch and often ate from the same mess trays. One Marine we all called, Bro, wasn't black at all. He was Ronald Allan Moore a blue eyed blond hair all surfer looking Marine from Manhattan Beach. He was a Marine that cared about his men but was not hesitant to kill gooks. Often back on base Hill 65, Vietnamese kids huddled around him and he played around with them, calling them little Charlies. <br>
One of the first things Bro said to me when I came to guns was &quot;Never volunteer for anything.&quot; <br>
On the morning of July 19th, 1967, he needed a gunner for the M-60. It was my turn to go but I had just gotten off watch. So, he choose instead to take the gun out himself. He was our squad leader and could have ordered anyone of us to go out that morning but he choose to take it out himself. <br>
As I laid on the cold Vietnamese ground huddled up trying to stay warm with only my flak jacket for a cover Bro took off his utility jacket and placed it over me. I awoke to its warmness but did not say thank you. You didn't do things like that to a Jarhead. But then again you didn't usually do caring things like Bro did. That is why everyone loved him and we all felt the pain when the fire team was ambushed. A Marine that was suppose to be on watch turned coward and ran, another Ken Stoker was immediately killed and only Turner a large black 6'2&quot; Marine and Bro remained. <br>
As the NVA soldiers advanced on their position Bro turned to Turner and said. &quot;Only one of us is going to get out alive, you better go. By then, both had been hit. Turner took off was shot a total of nine times but crawled back to our position. Moore received the Navy Cross for his actions but the certificate does not say anything about his volunteering for that mission or his caring deeds. It reflects his Marine training and dedication to duty and honor. How can you figure out a Marine like that? <br><br>
To refer to the war in Vietnam as a family feud is like saying the police should not be involved in investigating or seeking out gang members involved in home invasion robberies.  I have written many articles on the communist method of terrorist training, it was very effectively employed in Vietnam, and its propaganda machine was just as effective in the states.  We fought the commies in Viet Nam but were not prepared to fight them at home because they enjoyed the same freedom we tried to gain for the village farmers in Nam. The village people did not, did not want the North in their county, they did not want corruption governing over their lives and they voiced it in the election booth while I was there. They wanted and still do want the same type of freedom Americans enjoy.<br><br>

